'''Taoist Art''' relates to the [[Taoism|Taoist]] philosophy and narratives of Lao-tzu that promote "living simply and honestly and in harmony with nature."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Taoism|title=Definition of TAOISM|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-19}}</ref> [[File:Konfuzius-laozi.jpg|frameless|575x575px|Confucius meets Laozi|center]]The artists were "Daoist masters, adepts, scholars-amateurs, and even emperors..." thus an eclectic group of art works were created over time that are as varied as their makers .<ref>Augustin, Birgitta. “Daoism and Daoist Art.” In ''Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History''. New York: The Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2000–. <nowiki>http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/daoi/hd_daoi.htm</nowiki> (December 2011)</ref> {| |+ | rowspan="2" |''Robe embroidered with 5 dragons hovering over a landscape of mountains and ocean, likely worn by a Taoist priest during ceremonies.'' |- |}
[[File:MET DT4777.jpg|thumb|''Daoist Robe,'' 17th Century|450x450px]][[File:明 傳謝環 杏園雅集圖 卷-Elegant Gathering in the Apricot Garden MET DP273860.jpg|明 傳謝環 杏園雅集圖 卷-Elegant Gathering in the Apricot Garden MET DP273860|553x553px]]
== Concept == The philosophy of Taoism traces back to the late [[Bronze Age]] (third - fifth centuries B.C.), and later developed into a set of religious practices. Currently Taoism is considered a "living religion, practiced in Taiwan, Hong Kong, and many overseas Chinese communities, and one that is undergoing a major revival in mainland Chinas today.” p.&nbsp;13 <ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/44117921|title=Taoism and the arts of China|last=1954-|first=Little, Stephen,|date=2000|publisher=Art Institute of Chicago|others=Eichman, Shawn.|isbn=9780520227842|edition=1st|location=Chicago|oclc=44117921}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ucpress.edu/op.php?isbn=9780520227859|title=Out Of Print : Taoism and the Arts of China : Stephen Little - University of California Press|website=www.ucpress.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-19}}</ref>
An exhibition called ''[http://www.artic.edu/taoism/menu.php Taoism and the Arts of China]'', presented at [[Art Institute of Chicago|The Chicago Institute of Art]] (2000) emphasized the art of the late [[Han dynasty|Han]] to [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] dynasties and followed "the transformations of Taoism into an organized religion, the Taoist pantheon of gods who inhabit the stars and the heavens, modes of ritual and visualization, the cult of the immortals, and the role of landscape as a symbol of cosmic structure and process.”<ref name=":0" />
